text:
Manhattan Ave., west side, between Maujer and Stagg Streets. In the foreground, are razed buildings covering an area of 2 square blocks. At the right is Maujer Street, and P.S. No. 18. In the center background, is the R.C. Church of St. Mary of the Immaculate Conception, with its school and convent on Leonard Street.

December 23, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

Manhattan Ave., east side, between Maujer and Ten Eyck Streets, showing the site upon which was No. 210, a 3-story stucco building. At the left, is the rear of a 4-story frame building, (No. 128 Maujer Street), that adjoins the building at the S.E. corner.

September 27, 1935,

P. L. Sperr.

original_title: Brooklyn: Manhattan Avenue - Ten Eyck Street
text:
204-206 Manhattan Ave., at the N.E. corner of Ten Eyck Street. Also seen is Ten Eyck Street, east from Manhattan Ave., and Ten Eyck Street, is watching the eviction of those unwilling to move. These buildings have been razed and modern apartments are here, made possible by the Federal Housing Act.

August 26, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

132 Maujer Street, near the S.E. corner of Manhattan Ave., showing a frame home typical of this neighborhood which are quickly being replaced.

October 25, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

136-144 Maujer Street, south side, between Manhattan and Graham Aves; buildings razed under the Federal Housing Act, to make way for new low rental apartments.

July 30, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

Maujer Street, south side, east of Manhattan to Graham Aves., showing on the right, the rears of homes on the north side of Ten Eyck Street, and east of Manhattan Ave. Upon this site will be erected modern apartment dwellings under the Federal Housing Administration.

September 26, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

Maujer Street, south side, between Manhattan and Graham Aves., (rear houses). This is a view often seen in the Williamsburg area. These homes were built behind homes with no street frontage. Tenants used narrow passage ways to get in and out. This view is behind No. 142 Maujer Street. These buildings are soon to be demolished, to make way for new modern apartments.

September 26, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

Manhattan Ave., south from Maujer Street, showing a view of the new low cost housing buildings erected under the sponsorship of the F. H. A. and the City of New York.

July 23, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
